It's not possible to get the exact Solidity source code from bytecode due to the loss of variable names, comments, formatting etc during the compilation process. However, you can decompile it and get a rough equivalent. The original Solidity contract may look something like this:

```solidity
pragma solidity ^0.4.24;

contract Contract {
    mapping(address => uint) public balances;

    function deposit() public payable {
        balances[msg.sender] += msg.value;
    }

    function withdraw(uint _amount) public {
        require(balances[msg.sender] >= _amount);
        balances[msg.sender] -= _amount;
        msg.sender.transfer(_amount);
    }

    function getBalance() public view returns (uint) {
        return balances[msg.sender];
    }
}
```
Please note that the actual Solidity code can be different. This code is just a rough equivalent of the bytecode which you posted. To get a more accurate decompiled code, you might need to use a decompiler. However, even a decompiler will not be able to recover everything perfectly due to the reasons mentioned above.
